	abstract = {Bipolar disorder is still a more common misdiagnosis of mood disorders because its affective symptoms co-occur with unipolar depression, which leads to delay in treatment and clinical deterioration. This work proposes an objective framework by which to analyze mood responses of facial expressions through Action Unit (AU) representations for detection of bipolar-like affective patterns to mitigate this diagnostic challenge. MediaPipe Face Mesh was used to extract AU intensity features on FER2013 data based on Facial Action Coding System (FACS) features. Two classification models are created and compared: a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) for non-linear representation learning and Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) method for decision model ensemble. Data from experiments showed that MLP yielded an accuracy of 83% due to precision = 1.00, recall = 0.76, and F1-score = 0.86 for non-bipolar class, precision = 0.65, recall = 1.00, F1-score = 0.79 for bipolar class, an overall AUC = 0.95. The XGBoost model had a better accuracy of 89%, which includes precision = 0.996, recall = 0.845, and F1-score = 0.914 for the non-bipolar class, precision = 0.743, recall = 0.993, F1-score = 0.850, and an AUC of 0.97. These findings show class separability and generalization are better for XGBoost, whereas MLP shows good sensitivity for detecting bipolar-like patterns. Therefore, AU-based learning proves an alternative for early bipolar disorder screening that is non-invasive, interpretable, and computationally efficient. The spatiotemporal model and multimodal feature integration will further serve them in the future to increase both diagnostic reliability and clinical applicability. © 2025 IEEE.},
