	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105016548706?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Aim: This study compares the performance of XGBoost and Support Vector Machine (SVM) for breast cancer classification with the objectives of improving accuracy and precision to aid in early diagnosis and treatment. Materials and Methods: The study consists of two groups: Group 1 employs SVM as a reference model with an accuracy of 94.5%, whereas Group 2 utilizes XGBoost, which performs better than SVM with an accuracy of 97.1%. The dataset was preprocessed, features extracted, and classified, with performance measured by accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score. Results: XGBoost performed at 97.1% accuracy, higher than SVM's 94.5%, with much better precision and recall. This reaffirms XGBoost's better classification performance. Conclusion: XGBoost is a more powerful model for classifying 1 breast cancer than SVM, with more accuracy and reliability, and is thus a potentially valuable tool in early cancer detection for medical diagnostics. © 2025 IEEE.},
