	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105023990195?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Low-information-density webpages present significant challenges for web content extraction, often yielding fragmented text and high noise levels-issues that become especially critical when preparing large-scale corpora for training Large Language Models (LLMs). In this paper, we introduce a low-noise content extraction framework that integrates node-level XGBoost classification with a global reverse coloring procedure. Specifically, our method first classifies noisy nodes by learning localized DOM features, then refines these predictions via subtree-level merging and pruning to enforce structural consistency. Experimental results show that this approach outperforms a variety of baseline tools and LLM-driven extraction methods across multiple metrics. Notably, the reverse coloring step substantially mitigates local misclassifications while improving coherence in extracted text blocks. Our findings underscore the value of combining local classification signals with global DOM constraints, thereby enabling more robust, efficient extraction of high-quality web data-an essential requirement for large-scale LLM training pipelines. © 2025 IEEE.},
