	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105037321122?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {In highly imbalanced binary classification tasks with asymmetric misclassification costs, traditional cost-insensitive learning strategies fail to reflect true risk and often yield poor minority-class detection. This paper proposes a unified costsensitive framework that integrates weighted loss construction, cost-driven threshold optimization, and moderate oversampling, using XGBoost as the base model to incorporate cost information into both training and decision processes. Instance-level cost weighting strengthens gradients for high-cost classes, while empirical cost minimization on a validation set aligns probability outputs with optimal decision thresholds. Experiments on real NIPT data show that the proposed framework substantially improves the detection of high-cost minority cases under extreme rarity and maintains robust performance across multiple cost ratios. The framework is broadly applicable to other risksensitive and highly imbalanced domains, including financial risk control and industrial monitoring. © 2025 IEEE.},
