	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032183594?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {In the machine learning process, handling heterogeneous and imbalanced data remains a challenge. Some machine learning algorithms can only handle numeric data, one of which is the XGBoost classification algorithm. Previous studies on lung disease classification have not explained the technique of transforming categorical data into numeric form before entering the modeling process. This study uses four encoding techniques - one-hot encoding, frequency encoding, information-theory-based encoding, and renyi entropy-based encoding - on three heterogeneous and imbalanced lung disease datasets. The encoding results are used as input for the modeling process with XGBoost for lung disease classification, and evaluation using accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score metrics is conducted. From the comparison results, it was found that the choice of encoding technique has an impact on the classification performance of the XGBoost model. For datasets with balanced classes and even distribution, the one-hot-encoding and frequency-encoding techniques support the XGBoost model to achieve good performance. However, for datasets with imbalanced classes, information theory-based encoding techniques and renyi entropy support the model to achieve better precision and recall results. This research contributes to a systematic assessment of the selection of categorical data encoding techniques into numerical form so that it can produce models with more optimal performance, especially in cases of heterogeneous and imbalanced data.  © 2025 IEEE.},
	type = {Conference paper},
	publication_stage = {Final},
	source = {Scopus},
