	abstract = {Liquidity risk is a key indicator of financial stability, particularly for publicly traded firms. Traditional assessment methods often fall short in capturing complex patterns in financial data, especially in emerging markets such as Indonesia. This study presents a comparative analysis of three machine learning algorithms: Support Vector Machine (SVM), Decision Tree (DT), and Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) for classifying corporate liquidity risk based on financial statement data from companies listed on the Indonesia Stock Exchange (IDX). To address data imbalance, the Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique (SMOTE) was employed, and Grid Search was used for hyperparameter optimization. Additionally, SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) was applied to enhance model transparency by revealing feature importance. The results show that XGBoost outperformed SVM and DT in predictive accuracy and robustness, while SHAP interpretation confirmed the relevance of liquidity ratios in model decisions. This research highlights the effectiveness of ensemble learning and explainable AI in supporting early warning systems for liquidity risk in the financial sector.  © 2025 IEEE.},
