	abstract = {Influenza A, a zoonotic virus potentially affecting and infecting humans, poses a significant global health threat. This research paper presents a comprehensive study on predicting Influenza A outbreaks by applying the XGBoost classification algorithm. The study utilizes two substantial datasets: one from the World Health Organization (WHO) containing global Influenza A epidemiological data from 2003 to 2023 and the other encompassing Influenza A infections in New York counties from 2009 to 2019. Both datasets underwent pre-processing, with essential features selected to develop an XGBoost Classification model for forecasting Influenza A cases in humans. The models exhibited impressive accuracy and performance metrics. Specifically, the WHO dataset demonstrated an AUC of 0.996 and an accuracy score of 0.99, while the New York dataset displayed an AUC of 0.992 and an accuracy score of 0.978. These outcomes underscore the model's capability to differentiate between positive and negative cases, showcasing high precision, accuracy, and F1 scores. The implications of this research extend to various domains, including the early detection of outbreaks, informed decision-making processes, and the implementation of public health interventions. The findings emphasize the pivotal role of high-quality and comprehensive datasets in training effective predictive models. Furthermore, the study points towards potential future avenues, such as personalized predictions, geo-spatial analysis, and integrating these predictive models with healthcare systems.  © 2024 IEEE.},
