	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1109/IMPACT68503.2026.11468289},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105037428916?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {With an estimated 936 million adults affected globally, sleep apnea (SA) is a serious and prevalent sleep disorder that leads to a significant public health challenge. Early and accurate detection of this disease is crucial for effective management and treatment. To address this problem, this study proposes a feature-based classification framework to detect sleep apnea events using a single-channel EEG signal. The EEG signals are preprocessed to remove artifacts and subsequently divided into five EEG frequency subbands, i.e., delta, theta, alpha, sigma, and beta, using band-pass filtering. Eight distinct features are computed over each 10-second epoch for all EEG subbands, resulting in 40 features per subject. Feature selection is performed using an embedded feature importance method based on an XGBoost classifier, and correlated features are removed to reduce the feature vector. The performance of the XGBoost classifier is evaluated to classify apnea and normal events. Experimental results showed that the proposed method achieved an average classification accuracy of 94.68%, with a sensitivity of 93.30% and a specificity of 95.90% across all subjects. Comparative analysis with existing methods in the literature highlights the superior performance of the proposed approach. © 2026 IEEE.},
