	abstract = {The increasing demand for consistent and efficient agricultural rice quality assessment highlights the need for automated and reliable classification systems. Traditional manual methods are labor-intensive, time-consuming, and susceptible to human error, creating a critical gap that machine learning can address. This study presents a novel hybrid framework integrating VGG16 for feature extraction and XGBoost for classification, optimized using Bayesian Optimization. VGG16's deep convolutional architecture extracts rich hierarchical features from rice grain images, while XGBoost offers robust and interpretable classification. Bayesian Optimization efficiently tunes hyperparameters, enhancing performance with reduced computational overhead. Experimental results demonstrate the framework's exceptional performance, achieving a classification accuracy of 99.3%, precision of 1.00, recall of 0.99, F1-score of 0.99, and ROC-AUC of 0.99 on the test dataset. Comparative analysis with baseline models-including CNN (89.58% accuracy), VGG (88.0% accuracy), ResNet (87.0% accuracy), and VGG+XGBoost (93.0% accuracy)-revealed that the optimized VGG16+XGBoost framework significantly outperforms existing methods across all evaluation metrics. The system exhibits high scalability, making it suitable for large-scale agricultural operations and real-time monitoring systems in smart agriculture. This study validates the effectiveness of hybrid machine learning frameworks and highlights their potential to transform agricultural practices by providing advanced, scalable, and accurate solutions for crop quality assessment. © 2025 IEEE.},
