	abstract = {Accurate prediction of chili fruit grades prior to harvest is essential to support early-stage agricultural decision-making. This paper proposes a machine learning-based classification approach to predict chili grades - A, B, and C - using weekly vegetative features, such as plant height, leaf count, stem diameter, and growth stage. The modeling framework adopts the CRISP-DM methodology, encompassing data understanding, feature engineering, and model evaluation. Three models were developed and compared: a single-stage XGBoost, a multilayer perceptron (MLP), and a proposed two-stage XGBoost pipeline that first distinguishes Grade C from non-C, followed by classification between Grades A and B. Experimental results demonstrate that the two-stage XGBoost model achieved the highest performance, with an accuracy of 0.83 and a macro F1-score of 0.82, significantly outperforming both baselines in addressing class imbalance and feature overlap. Engineered features - particularly growth rate and interaction terms - proved critical in enhancing class separability and prediction accuracy. Despite the limitations and noise present in real-world data, the final model demonstrated strong generalization capability, stability, and robustness across all classes. These results highlight the effectiveness of hierarchical modeling, structured-data learning, and domain-informed features in addressing practical classification challenges. Ultimately, this work contributes to the development of low-cost, interpretable, and field-ready decision-support systems for smallholder farmers through accessible machine learning tools.  © 2025 IEEE.},
