	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105025476729?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Heart rhythm disturbances (arrhythmias) in the elderly are chronic conditions that are high risk and often difficult to detect early because the symptoms are not always obvious. Automatic detection of electrical signals of the heart is important to improve the accuracy of early detection. This study proposes the use of the XGBoost algorithm for the classification of arrhythmias in the elderly because of its high ability to handle big data, reduce overfitting, and provide high accuracy. Data were obtained from several elderly subjects through two activity scenarios, namely sitting and walking, each for 1 minute 30 seconds. The data were classified into four categories: normal, abnormal, potentially arrhythmic, and highly potentially arrhythmic. The results showed that the XGBoost algorithm was able to achieve an accuracy of 96.15% in classifying heart conditions, indicating its effectiveness in early detection of arrhythmias. These findings indicate that machine learning algorithms have great potential to be used to maintain the heart health of the elderly automatically and in a timely manner.  © 2025 IEEE.},
