	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105005024494?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {To address the issues of domain discrepancies and limited labeled samples in hyperspectral image classification of cross scene, this paper proposes an ensemble learning framework that integrates eXtreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) with confidence domain adaptation strategies to improve classification performance. First, the Houston dataset from different scenes is input separately into a deep embedding model. The hyperspectral images are embedded into a low-dimensional space, ensuring that similar spectra are represented more closely in this space, thereby capturing the intrinsic structure and distribution of the hyperspectral image dataset. Subsequently, these samples are mapped into a discriminator model, where domain adaptation techniques are employed to reduce differences in feature distributions across different scenes. Additionally, confidence-based learning is used to identify and remove noisy samples in the Houston dataset, thereby enhancing the alignment of feature distributions among various scenes. Finally, through ensemble learning, a weighted voting strategy is employed to combine multiple base classifiers into a strong classification model. This approach better captures the complex features within the data, thereby reducing the bias of individual classifiers and enhancing the overall generalization ability and robustness of the model. Experimental results on the Houston dataset demonstrate that the proposed method outperforms popular domain adaptation learning models and traditional methods in terms of classification accuracy and robustness, showcasing its potential and advantages in practical applications. This result confirms the effectiveness of combining XGBoost and confidence domain adaptation strategies in handling hyperspectral image classification. © 2025 SPIE.},
