	abstract = {Malware attack refers to the hacker or attacker through various means, malicious software (such as viruses, trojans, spyware, etc.) implanted into the victim's computer or mobile device, in order to steal personal information, steal property, damage the system and other purposes. By comparing the effect of XGBoost classification, BP neural network classification and CatBoost classification on malware attack prediction, this paper summarizes and analyzes the advantages and disadvantages of each algorithm. The experimental results show that XGBoost classification model has the best accuracy, reaching 99.1%, while the accuracy of BP neural network classification model is 98.2%, and the accuracy of CatBoost classification model is only 82.8%. XGBoost and CatBoost are both machine learning algorithms based on gradient tree, while BP neural network is a neural network based algorithm. Comparing the three algorithms in principle, it can be found that XGBoost performs well on large-scale data, CatBoost performs well on class-unbalanced data, and BP neural networks require more training data to achieve better results. The research in this paper provides a certain research basis for the subsequent malware attack prediction, and also provides a reference for the selection of machine learning algorithms. © 2023 IEEE.},
