	abstract = {Diagnosing and treating cerebrovascular diseases relies on two critical tasks: identifying brain blood clots and predicting the specific type of stroke. The most frequent type of stroke is ischemic stroke, which occurs when there are blockages in the arteries near the brain. This type of stroke is characterized by typical symptoms such as paralysis, memory impairment, and alterations in behavior. However, specific stroke subtypes, such as Large Artery Atherosclerosis (LAA) and Cardioembolic (CE), require precise identification for accurate patient diagnosis. To tackle this challenge, artificial intelligence techniques were employed, involving feature extraction and machine learning methods. The dataset used in this study consisted of high-resolution blood clot images in TIFF file format, which exhibited an imbalance. Image augmentation techniques, in combination with feature extraction using the Histogram of Oriented Gradients (HOG) method, were employed. Machine learning algorithms, including Decision Tree (DT), Random Forest (RF), Extreme Boosting (XGB), and RF-based XGB, were applied to classify stroke types (CE or LAA) based on blood clot characteristics. Notably, the performance of HOG followed by RF on a balanced dataset outperformed all other models, achieving an accuracy of 80.08%. © 2025 Author(s).},
