	abstract = {The increasing presence of unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) near sensitive areas has heightened the demand for intelligent threat classification systems. Previous research applied trajectory-based classification using Support Vector Machines (SVM), achieving moderate accuracy but demonstrating limited effectiveness in real-world threat detection. This study introduces a novel integrated framework that combines advanced behavior-based classification with utilitydriven decision-making for UAV threat assessment. Unlike prior approaches, the framework explicitly targets two high-risk UAV behaviors-loitering and high-speed approach-which are strongly associated with surveillance and attack scenarios. Flight path features such as dwell time, turning frequency, and velocity variation are analyzed using the XGBoost algorithm to provide probabilistic threat estimates. These outputs are then systematically processed through a utility-based decision model, which selects optimal responses-ignore, track, alert, or intercept-based on adjustable utility functions that capture both threat severity and operational priorities. By uniting behavior-specific classification with a flexible, utility-guided reasoning layer, the proposed system not only improves detection accuracy but also enhances contextual responsiveness. This dual-layered approach represents a significant advancement over existing methods, offering a more robust and adaptable solution for real-Time counter-drone operations.  © 2025 IEEE.},
